SIMPLE: glove
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Glove
<hw>Glove</hw> <pr>(gl⟦ucr⟧v)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>glove</ets>, <ets>glofe</ets>, AS. <ets>gl⟦omac⟧f</ets>; akin to
Icel. <ets>gl⟦omac⟧fi</ets>, cf. Goth. <ets>l⟦omac⟧fa</ets> palm of the
hand, Icel. <ets>l⟦omac⟧fi</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A cover for the hand, or for the hand and wrist,
with a separate sheath for each finger. The latter characteristic
distinguishes the <xex>glove</xex> from the <xex>mitten</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A boxing glove.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Boxing glove</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Boxing</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Glove fight</b></col>, <cd>a pugilistic
contest in which the fighters wear boxing gloves.</cd> --
<mcol><col><b>Glove money</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Glove
silver</b></col></mcol>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>A tip or gratuity to servants,
professedly to buy gloves with.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <fld>(Eng. Law.)</fld>
<cd>A reward given to officers of courts; also, a fee given by the
sheriff of a county to the clerk of assize and judge's officers, when
there are no offenders to be executed.</cd> -- <col><b>Glove
sponge</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a fine and soft variety of
commercial sponges (<spn>Spongia officinalis</spn>).</cd> -- <col><b>To
be hand and glove with</b></col>, <cd>to be intimately associated or on
good terms with.</cd> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Hand and glove with</xex>
traitors.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>J. H. Newman.</au> -- <col><b>To handle without
gloves</b></col>,<-- with the gloves off, to take the gloves off -->
<cd>to treat without reserve or tenderness; to deal roughly with.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark> -- <col><b>To take up the glove</b></col>, <cd>to
accept a challenge or adopt a quarrel.</cd> -- <col><b>To throw down the
glove</b></col>, <cd>to challenge to combat.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Glove</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Glove
<hw>Glove</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Gloved</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Gloving</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To cover with, or as with, a
glove.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>gloved</ent>⟦br⟧
